{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_lavender_ver01/data/sn88078775/0034058076A/1924022201/0832.xml":{"full_text":"V\u2018! mw^'v'1\u2019\nX-\u2019\nPAGE SIX\nTRADES AND LABOR ASSEMBLY\nNext Sunday morning, February\n24, is the regular meeting of Newark\nTrades and Labor Assembly. Some\nfrnportant business will come up, and\nit is the duty of every member to be\non hand. Meeting called to order at\nten o\u2019clock sharp\u2014this don\u2019t mean\nhalf-past ten or eleven. Be\nsure, and get there on time.\nthere\nRESOLUTIONS OF RESPECT\nTo the family of our late Com\npanion and Brother, Frank Verheyen,\na member of the Brewery Workers\nand Coal Miners Unions, and one of\nthe Trades and Labor Assembly\u2019s\nmost faithful officers, who we have\nhonored with a Life Membership in\nthat body.\nDear Friends:\nIt was with the deepest sympathy\nthat the Assembly received the notice\nof your father\u2019s death, and at the\nregular meeting of the Assembly,\nheld February 13, 1924, the following\nresolutions were adopted.\nBe it resolved: That in the death\nof our brother and fellow worker,\nFrank Verheyen, Union Labor has\nlost one of its hardest and most faith\nful workers, at all times for the ad\nvancement of labor, and for the bet\nterment of all classes of the working\nman. Be it further\nResolved, That as a mark of appre\nciation of our late brother\u2019s services,\nour charter be draped for thirty days,\nand that these resolutions be spread\nupon our minutes, and a copy be fur\nnished our journal, the Newark Lead\ner, for publication and sent to\nfamily of our deceased brother.\n(Signed)\nthe\nW. H. Cocanour,\nRobert Williams,\nCliff Rosehrough,\nCommittee on\nResolutions.\nAdopted February 13, 1924.\nDeath of Mrs. Moriarty\nMrs. Mahala Litten Moriarty, wife\nof Daniel H. Moriarty, B. O. tele\ngrapher and president of the B. O.\nVeterans Association, died Friday\nmorning at her home, 359 Clinton\nstreet, from heart trouble. She was\nborn December 7, 1862, and was mar\nried to Mr. Moriarty, April 21, 1904.\nShe is survived by her husband, one\nsister, Mrs. Frank Rian, of Webb\nstreet, and a brother, Wynn Litten,\nof Martinsburg. The funeral serv\nices were held Monday afternoon, at\nthe First Baptist church, Rev. Forest\nFrasier officiating, and burial made\nin Cedar Hill cemetery. At the time\nof her death Mrs. Moriarty was vice\npresident of the Woman\u2019s Auxiliary\nto the B. O. Veterans Association.\nLabor Official Visits Newark\nJoseph A. Bauer, the efficient\nretary of the Zanesville Trades\nLabor Council, made a business\nto Newark Saturday afternoon,\nof course paid the Leader a visit,\nwho is one of the best posted\nmost energetic labor leaders in Zanes\nville, reports everything in fine shape\nin his bailiwick, with a fine outlook\nfor a general business revival in\nspring.\nsec\nand\ntrip\nand\nJoe,\nand\nthe\nHANDLING A WOMAN\nELECTRICALLY.\nWhen a woman is sulky\nand w\u2019ill not speak Exciter\nIf she gets too excited Controller\nIf she talks too long Interrupter\nIf her way of thinking is\nnot yours Converter\nIf she is willing to come\nhalfway Meter\nIf she will come all the way....Receiver\nIf she wanted to go\nfurther Conductor\nIf she would go further Dispatcher\nIf she wanted to be an\nangel Transformer\nIf you think she is pick\ning your pockets...' Detector\nIf she proves your fears\nare wrong Compensator\ngoes up in the air....Condenser\nwants chocolates Feeder\nsings inharmoniously Tuner\nis in the country....Telegrapher\nis a poor cook Discharger\ndress unhooks Connector\neats too much Reducer\nis wrong Rectifier\nIf she\nIf she\nIf she\nIf she\nshe\nher\nshe\nshe\nher fingers and toes\nare cold Heater\nIf she gossips too much Regulator\nIf she fumes and sputters Insulator\nIf she becomes upset Reverser\nn\nn\nif\nif\nif\nLabor organizations are built upon\nthe principle of co-operation. To be\nsuccessful the individual members\nmust understand the necessity of co\noperating one with the other.\nCity Notes\nSpent Week End With Relatives\nMrs. A. J. Teagarden, of Warren,\nOhio, has returned home from a\nweek-end visit with Mr. and Mrs. J.\nS. Teagarden, of 75 Allston avenue.\nEarl Evans With Wallace Davidson\nThe popular and expert barber,\nEarl Evans, has accepted a position\nat the new establishment of Wallace\n.Davidson on North Park Place, where\nhe will be glad to meet his many\nfriends.\nMrs. East Entertains Club\nMrs. Louise East entertained the\nmembers of the White Carnation Re\nview Needle Club Wednesday evening\nof last week. Refreshments were\nserved seventeen members and one\nguest. Mrs. Charles Frields won the\ncontest prize.\nAlleged Chicken Thieves Bond Over\nFloyd Simes and Roy and Floyd\nCamp, charged with stealing chick\nens, after a hearing in municipal\ncourt Saturday afternoon, were bound\nover to the grand jury in the sum of\n$1,500 each, which being furnished,\nthey were released from custody.\nMore Fish for Buckeye Lake\nUpwards of 10,000 bass and blue\ngills were turned into Brickeye Lake\nlast Friday from the private hatch\neries of W. W. and A. T. Wehrle, and\nit is estimated that a million more\nfish are in the hatcherv ready to be\nturned out as soon as the ice\npears.\nRed Star Bus Ditched\nImportant Contract to Be Let\nJames McCarthv, 27 North Fifth\nstreet, secretary of the building com\nmittee of St. Francis de Sales church,\nwill receive sealed bids until noon of\nMarch 18, for the erection of the new\nschool building and central heating\nplant and furnishing necessary ma\nterials, in accordance with plans and\nspecifications now on file. The pro\nposals will be made out on uniform\nblanks, and the different branches in\ncluded are masonry, steel and iron\nwork, lathing and plastering, carpen\ntry, painting and varnishing, roofing\nand sheet metal work, marbleoid\nflooring, electrical work, plumbing,\nheating and ventilation. The success\nful bidder will be required to sign\ncontracts for the faithful execution of\nthe work and furnish bond in amount\nequal to fifty per cent of the con\ntract awarded. The proposals will be\nread to the public in Knights of Co\nlumbus club rooms, West Main street,\nat one o\u2019clock on the afternoon of\nMarch 18.\nWORKINGMEN\nCultivate the Habit of Purchasing\nUNION LABEL\nAnd be an Employer of Union Labor\nGIVE YOUR PREFERENCE TO\nTHE LEADER ADVERTISERS\nTHEY ASSIST YOUR CAUS~E\n'\u2022\u2018\u25a0i\ndisap-\nwhich\nseven\nA Red Star passenger bus\nleft Newark for Columbus at\no\u2019clock Sunday morning, skidded on\nthe road near Columbia Center and\nwent into the ditch. There was but\none passenger and neither he or the\ndriver were injured. The only dam\nage done was the breaking of several\nwindows.\nFriends Are Ever Welcome\nThis is the eleventh week of the\nconfinement of J. S. Teagarden to his\nhome on Allston avenue by complica\ntions following an attack of grip, and\ntime hangs heavy on his hands. Bro.\nTeagarden tells us the latch string is\never on the outside and that visits\nfrom friends are always welcome.\nDrop in and cheer the old boy up.\nDeath of J. A. Flory\nJesse A. Florv, aged seventh years,\none of the oldest practicing attorney?\nin the city, died at his home, 31C\nWest Church street last Saturday\nevening, from a complication of dis\neases. He is survived by his widow\nand two sons, both lawyers, Charles\nL., of this city, and Walter L., of\nCleveland. The funeral was held in\nthe Second Presbyterian church at\ntwo o\u2019clock Tuesday afternoon and\nburial made in Cedar Hill cemetery.\nBurns Cause Child\u2019s Death\nCatherine, the six-year-old daugh\nter of Mr. and Mrs. William E. Allen.\n120 East Locust street, was fatally\nburned by her nightgown taking fire\nfrom an open stove as she was dress\ning early Saturday morning, before\nthe other members of the family had\ncome down stairs. Everything poss\nible was done to relieve the child\u2019s\nsuffering and save her life, but all\nefforts were fruitless, and she died\nat half-past six o\u2019clock Saturday eve\nning. She is survived by her parents\nand two brothers. Funeral services\nwere held at St. Francis de Sales\nchurch Tuesday morning and burial\nmade in Mt. Calvary cemetery.\nTHE NEWARK\nThe People\u2019s Column\nCommunications are solicited on all\nsubjects, full name must be signed\nas an evidence of good faith. It is\nunderstood that this papei\u2019 does not\nindorse the sentiment of all commun\nications and is at liberty to take issue\nwhen deemed necessary.\nPROHIBITION A FARCE\nThere was a lovely field day in the\nHouse on Friday, Feb. 1st. Two not\nable speeches, both timely and tropi\ncal, enlivened an otherwise dull day.\nThe Hon. James A. Galli van, of Bos\nton, made a spectacular and pathetic\ntalk on the present moral conditions\nnot alone in Boston but everywhere.\nMr. Gallivan took strong ground for\nlaw enforcement but deeply depre\ncated the present outlawry and crime\nand paid due attention to some high\nup criminals. He gave some valuable\nstatistics from official sources. We\nquote:\n\u201cIn 22 states, with a total popula\ntion of 57,948,603, it is said by offi\ncers of the law that the non-enforce\nment of the Volstead law ranges from\n50 to 95 per cent and in the other 26\nstates, with a total population of 47,\n762,000, the average non-enforcement\nis from 5 to 45 per cent.\u201d\nIn referring to the Rev. Anderson,\nsuperintendent of the Anti-Saloon\nleague of New York, just found guilty\nby a jury, of embezzlement and forg\nery and perjury, Gallivan said:\n\u201cI shall vote for this appropriation\nbill carrying an appropriation of al\nmost $11,000,000 for the enforcement\nof the Volstead law, but I do not be\nlieve that the expenditure of money\nwill bring any better respect for the\nlaw or any better enforcement. Mr.\nWheeler is not master of the Anti\nSaloon League romance. The recog\nnized master of romance in the\nLeague and in America is that great\n'leader just convicted for forgery in\nNew York, Rev. William H. Ander\nson, who in his testimony last week\nmade the stories of the Arabian\nNights appear dull and common\nplace.\u201d\nCongressman Hill, Republican, of\nMaryland, who announced that he\nwas not going to make either a wet\nor a dry speech, occupied thirty min\nutes telling the country how some of\nthe many million dollars of tax money\ngiven to the Anti-Saloon League was\nspent in 1923. The appropriation for\nthe league this year is about two mil\nlions more than in 1923, when $9,\n000.000 was spent on officers alone.\nThe thirteen prohibition lawyers\ndrew $147,000 last year. It seems\nthe prohibition officers spent last\nvear, as shown by Congressman Hill,\nRepublican, over $205,000 for whis\nkey. They bought over $205,000\nworth of whiskey to be used in the\ndetective service. Detectives figuring\nas liquor merchants selling liquor to\nbootleggers and citizens and then\nhave such persons arrested as viola\ntors of the Volstead Act.\nIn other words, the prohibition\nagents violated the law in order to\nconvict other violators of the law.\nCongressman Hill held that such con\nduct was disreputable and immoral.\nHill\u2019s closing words in this system\nare as follows:\n\u201cIn other words we have men in\nthis country, stool pigeons to violate\nthe laws they are .sworn to enforce in\norder to attempt to gain convic\ntions.\u201d\nThanking you for publishing the\nabove articles in an early issue, we\nremain.\nYours very truly,\nCommittee From Branch 24,\nG. B. B. A.\nGEM\nTODAY\u2014TOMORROW\n\u201cTHE STEEL TRAIL\u201d\n\u2014WITH\u2014\nWilliam Duticati\n\u2014ALSO\u2014\nBilly Sullivan\n\u2014IN\u2014\n\u201cThe Leather Pushers\u201d\n\u2014ADDED\u2014\n\u201cCOMEDY\u201d\nSUNDAY\n\u201cBATTLING BATES\u201d\nSATURDAY\u2014SUNDAY\nARROW\nBROKEN\nVIOLIN\"\nwith\nStory hy\n'MoBucto ar\nATLANTIC\nfutures,\nREED HOWES\nZENA KEEFE\nDOROTHY MACKAILl\nRITA ROGAN\nGLADDEN JAMES\nHENRY SEDLEY\nJACK\nRICHARDSON\nGEORCE ROGAN\nDirected by\nJACK DILLON\nLEADER\nTHINGS WORTH WHILE\n(By Mabel Brown Denison)\nDon\u2019t ask, \u201cHas the world been a\nfriend to me?\u201d\nBut, \u201cHave I to the world been true?\u201d\n\u2019Tis not what you get, but what you\ngive\nThat makes life worth while to\n\u2019Tis the kind word said to the\nchild\nAs you wiped its tears away,\nAnd the smile you brought to\ncareworn face\nThat really lights up your day.\nyou.\nlittie\nsome\n\u2019Tis the hand you clasp with an hon\nest grasp\nThat gives you a hearty thrill,\n\u2019Tis the good you pour into other\nlives\nThat comes back your own to fill.\n\u2019Tis the dregs you drain from\nanother\u2019s cup\nThat makes your own seem sweet,\nAnd the hours you give to your\nbrother man\nThat makes your own life complete.\n\u2019Tis the burdens you help another\nbear\nThat makes your own seem light.\n\u2019Tis the dangers seen for another\u2019s\nfeet\nTh nt show you the path to right.\n\u2019Tis the good you do each passing day\nWith a heart sincere and true\u2014\n\"For through giving the world your\nwry best\nIts best will return to you.\n\u2014Stone Cutters\u2019 Journal.\nUnion Membership Increases\nWashington\u2014At least one trade\nunion has gained in membership\nsince the war peak, according to the\nlatest report of F. E. Langdon, gen\neral secretary, Steam Shovel and\nDredgemen, whose headquarters are\nhere. They had only 10,000 men in\n1918-19, while now they have nearly\n11,500.\nThe child who demands the Union\nLabel wields more influence than the\nman or woman who strikes. The\nstrikers\u2019 place may be filled, but there\nis no substitute for the Union Label.\nNOTICE 10 OWNERS\nOf DOGS\nAll owners of dogs, who have not\nsecured thrir license for 1924 are\nhereby notified to secure the same\nat once, and avoid prosecution, as the\nDeputy Sheriff in charge of registra\ntion of dogs in Licking County, be\ngins a canvass of this County on Mon\nday, March 3rd, 1924 for unregister\ned dogs.\nAll owners not having the 1924\nlicense will be prosecuted and fined\nfrom $5 to $25 on each offense and\neach dog shall constitute a separate\noffense.\nFRED H. VOGELMEIER,\nSheriff Licking County.\nGRAND\nHome of the Symphony Organ\nFRIDAY AND SATURDAY\nWILLIAM S. HART\n\u2014IN\u2014\n\u2018Travelin\u2019 On\u201d\nEXTRA ADDED\nGEORGE O\u2019HARA\n\u2014IN\u2014\nA New \u201cFighting Blood\u201d Story\nSUNDAY AND MONDAY\nWm. P. Earle\u2019s Production\n\u201cTHE DANCER\nOF THE NILE\u201d\nWith CARMEL MYERS\nMalcolm MacGregor, Sam de Grassi,\nBertram Grassby, June Elvidge.\nA PASSIONATE LOVE STORY OF\nTHE DAYS OF KING TUT.\nAll the lure, all the charm, all the\nmystery of history\u2019s most fascinating\nperiod, woven into a story that will\nkeep your interest at fever heat from\nthe first flash to the fade-out.\n\u2014ADDED\u00ab~\u00bb\nRUTH ROLAND\nRUTH OF THE RANGE\u201d\nAnd a Hal Roach Comedy\nFOUR DAYS STARTING\nTUESDAY\nDavid Belasco\u2019s Big Success\n\u201cThe Gold Diggers\u201d\nWith Hope Hampton, Wyndham\nStanding, Louise Fazenda\nGold digging in New York\u2014Yes\u2014but\nnot with pick and shovel\u2014Oh, No!\nThe modern fair \u201cdigger extracts the\nprecious metal with vampish eyes and\ntantalizing lips.\nSee the inside of the new art of \u201cgold\ndigging\u201d as practiced by some of the\ngirls of New York in\nWarner Bros.\u2019 Big Screen Hit\n\u201cT#E GOLD DIGGERS\u201d\nAn extraordinary and spectacular\nproduction, daringly realistic\ngiving an entirely new slant on\nYou\u2019ll Be Very, Very Sorry If\nand\nlife.\nYou\nMiss \u201cThe Gold Diggers\u201d\nNote Prices During This Engagement\nADULTS 30c CHILDREN 15c\nJACK ALLEN CO.\nHAVE MOVED THEIR\nPLUMBING OFFICE\nAND SHOP FROM 205\nEAST MAIN ST. TO\nNORTH PARK PLACE\nWith Martin Bros. Laun\ndry Equipment Co., where\na full line of plumbing\nfixtures and supplies will\nbe carried.\nTelephone\n1633\nTODAY AND SATURDAY\nBOBB OTT\nAND HIS MUSICAL COMEDY CO.\nTONIGHT\u2014AMATEURS\nPRIZES TO WINNERS\nSATURDAY\nTHE CLEVER SHOW\nSUNDAY\nSPECIAL ADDED FEATURES\n\u2666\u2018Where the\nPavement Ends\u201d\nADDED\nCOMEDY\u2014NEWS\u2014FABLES\nSTARTING MONDAY\nTaken in action by the Signal Corps of the U. S. Army and\ncompiled in one stupendous picture showing\npie history of America\u2019s part in the\nRather\n\u25a0R&r\ncommo\nAUDITORIUM\nFRIDAY, FEBRUARY 22nd, 192).\nCOMPARISON W1 ,1[LIVING ARTIST\nreveals5nBdifeerence\nTHE ONLY\nPHONOGRAPH\nIts \u201cREALISM\u201d has never been Equaled by\nAnything but the LIVING ARTIST.\nFOURTEEN MODELS\u2014$100.00 Up\nEASY TERMS\nEVERYTHING FOR THE HOME\nEyes Examined Glasses Fitted\nNewark,Ohio\nNext Door to Warden Hotel\nPATRONISE OUR ADVERTISERS\nFREE LECTURE\n\u2018THE GLORIOUS FUTURE\nFOR EARTH AND MAN\u201d\n\u2014\u201cmillions now living will never die.\u201d\nA BIBLICAL REVIEW OF FUTURE CONDITIONS\n\u2014BY\u2014\nSunday, Feb. 24,7:30 p.\nFREE NO COLLECTIONS\nAuspices International Bible Students Association\nOfficial War Department Films\nWORLD\nWAR\nSHOWING EVERY\nDIVISION LN ACTION\nFour Great Battles\nCHATEAU THIERRY\nCANTIGNY\nFEINBERG\u2019S\nMeet the Wife\u201d\nELK\u2019S MINSTRELS\nSA. A1IHIEL\nARGONNE\nSEE IT WITH YOUR\nOWN\u2019 EYES\nNo one can tell you about it.\nYou can\u2019t get it in books.\nAuspices of Frank S. Hoffer\nPost No. 1060\nVeterans of Foreign Wars\nTHEATER\nNEWARK, OHIO\nFebruary 28, 2Q and March 1\nALHAMBRA\nFRIDAY AND SATURDAY\nSHIRLEY MASON\nIN THE FOX STORY\nSUNDAY\nJack Hoxie\n\u2014IN\u2014\n\u201cMEN INjTHE RAW\u201d\nCOMEDY\u2014NEWS\u2014ETC.\nSTARTING MONDAY\n\u201cON THE BANKS Of\nTHE WABASH\u201d\nI4\n1\ni\ni\ns","height":"26517","width":"18126"}}
